Back to School! Here’s a college search piece I worked on with a few ol’ buddies at @truth.consequences for @earlhamcollege1847. They were kind enough to let me do my thing and even write some copy too. The “COMPOST” idea is just something I lifted from campus, so I can’t take full credit there (but I do absolutely love it).

Letterpress proofs for @wepresent using the lovely words of @olivialanguage. Thank you @shetromp & @type01_ for letting me print some things. I so enjoy inking up ol’ wood type, fussing over spacing, and being actually out of sorts. Adding dialogue with other creatives to get the type perfectly imperfect made the process even better ❤️🖨️

Wine ads made with wood, metal, and elbow grease. It was a pleasure to work with @heylabour and @selectwinemoments on these. Every element from the headline, logo, and even bottle was put through the printing process to give it all that warm organic feel. Also, thanks to @mrpeteross for letting me print some things 🖨️🍷

Happy b-day @kaijubeer!We’ve made bottles and cans, it’s time to clap your hands. This is the first time I’ve wished a brand a happy b-day, but there is some celebration in order. I’ve been working with the brothers at Kaiju Beer (and Clara, too) for over a decade. It’s been so fun collaborating with such a great team, and even though the entire world separates us, we’ve successfully made beautiful work. Here are some highlights of things we’ve made over the years. Here’s to another 10! Cheers, my friends.
Quick illustration for @theeconomist on helping Santa become more tech savvy 🎅🏼

NEW MIKEY BURTON DOT COM!
I took the end of 2023 to give the ol’ website a refresh. I didn’t try to reinvent the wheel, but the car needed a new set of tires. Where to start? It’s overwhelming looking through piles of work; time passes, styles change, and work can feel dated quickly. At the same time, It’s inspiring to see creative progress if you can ignore the missteps. Also, it fills me with overwhelming gratitude for those who took a chance and let me make some stuff. Thank you!

The first step was to set some rules. Something to guide me a bit and help me decide what work stays and what goes. Here they are:

MAIN THING: ONLY INCLUDE WORK YOU WANT TO MAKE 
and include things that…
• show a lot of thought
• show a lot of ideas
• have originality (mostly in style)
• true to me
• aren’t overworked
• are a little weird

That’s the work that made it on the site. What does all this mean, though? Yes! I’m looking. Looking for jobs, gigs, more freelance, opportunities, full-time, part-time, half-time, teaching, learning, etc. I love being creative. I also like money.

This old dog is ready for something new.

The site was built with @cargoworld
